Univariate Analysis

Tip: Now that youve completed your univariate explorations, its time to reflect on and summarize what youve found. Use the questions below to help you gather your observations and add your own if you have other thoughts!

What is the structure of your dataset?

Quality is the response variable in the dataset. The histogram displays that it is in normal distribution.

The explanatory variables in this dataset are quantitative. Some of them are explored in univariate plots:

  1. pH, fixed and volatile acidity, residual sugar and chlorides values are also in normal distribution, similar to quality values.

  2. Alcohol, total and free sulfur dioxide histograms are right skewed.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

Quality of the wine is a result of sulfur, acidity, sugar and chloride variables. Throughout the analysis below, I will assess the correlation between the quality and these variables.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your

Quality and the 1st group of variables above are in normal distribution. I will test whether this similarity in distribution means there is strong correlation between these variables and the resultant quality.

pH value can be a resultant value of fixed, volalite acidity and citric acid variables. I will assess whether there is a relationship between these variables and pH value.

Total and free sulfur dioxide distibutions are very similarly right skewed. I will also check whether these 2 variables are strongly corelated.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

At first check, no new variables are created.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?

Throughout the histograms, I removed the long tails of some of the variables by cutting from the 1st and 3rd quadrants so that I could focus on the main distribution omitting the outliers.

Citric acid values seem to be distributed throughout the histogram plot. I checked the log and sqrt distributions if there could be a gaussian distribution hidden.

Bivariate Plots Section

In this section, The correlation between different explanatory variables and the resultant variable, quality.

Lets start with creating a heatmap which displays the correlations between different variables.

In the heatmap, the following correlations can be observed: 1. In higher quality wines, the alcohol , sulphates and citric acid is found more. There is a positive relationship between quality and these variables. 2. Volatile acidity is found less in hihger quality wines where as citric acid increases. 3. pH value of the wine is negatively correlated to fixed acidity and citric acid and positively correlated with volatile acidity. 4. Fixed acidity is very strongly correlated to citric acid and density of the wine. 5. Total and free sulfur dioxide is strongly correlated with each other.

As a second step, I will make a detailed analysis of these correlations in below chapters.

The relationship between pH and Quality:

Inspecting the boxplots for each quality level, it can be observed that pH value is slightly decreasing while the quality of wine increases.

Contrary to my expectation, there is a weak correlation between the pH value and the quality. In the prior research about wine quality, it is said that pH value is important for the quality of wine.

The relationship between Fixed Acidity and Quality:

In general positive correlation is observed between Quality and Fixed Acidity. Fixed acidity in the wine increases in higher quality wines. However, there is not a continuous increase as fixed acidity values are nearly same in quality 3 and 8 wine samples.

The relationship between Volatile Acidity and Quality:

There is very strong negative relationship between the volatile acidity and the quality of the wine. As the quality increases, the volatile acidity is sharply decreasing.

There is a positive relationship between the quality and citric acid value of wine.

Throughout the assessment of relationship between quality and acidity variables, it is observed that the most strong relationship is between volatile acidity and quality. In order to make better understandable visual analysis, I decided to use Volatile Acidity as the acidity variable.

Bivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the
investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in
the dataset?

The response variable quality is positively correlated with fixed acidity, citric acid and alcohol. In higher quality wines, alcohol an fixed acid is found more.

On the other hand, the quality of the wine decreases when volatile acid, chloride and total sulfur dioxide increases in the wine. There is also a weak negative correlation between pH and the quality of the wine. We can say that high quality wines have lower pH values.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features
(not the main feature(s) of interest)?

I checked the relationship between pH and other acidity variables. The analysis shows us that pH is strongly negative correlated with fixed and citric acid variables, whereas it is positively correlated with volatile acidity. I also suspected if there is any corelation between pH and total sulfur dioxide but there is no such evidence.

Also I assessed the relationship between the total and free sulfur dioxide and there seems a strong positive relationship between these 2 variables.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

The strongest relationship is between the alcohol and the quality of the wine.

Linear model depicting the relationship between Quality, Volatile Acidity, Alcohol, Total Sulfur Dioxide and Chlorides

A linear model is created to formulate the linear relationship between Quality and the explanatory variables of Volatile Acidity, Alcohol, Total Sulfur Dioxide and Chlorides.

## m3: lm(formula = I(quality) ~ I(log(volatile.acidity)) + alcohol + 
##     total.sulfur.dioxide, data = RedWineQuality)

However, when we check the r-squared values, it seems that the linear model is far from covering the variance. This model can not be used to predict the quality level of wine with input values of Volatile Acidity, Alcohol, Total Sulfur Dioxide and Chlorides.

In order to create the above plot, the following steps are followed: 1. Bivariate plot of pH and Log of volatile acidity are used as a base. 2. The continuous varible Fixed acidity and citric acid are transformed into a categorical variables. In each category 3 levels are set. 3. The points are colored according to citric acid categories. 4. The shapes of posint are differentiated according to fixed acid categories.

Visual observations depict these findings: 1. pH is in positive correlation with volatile acidity.

  1. Citric acid is in negative correlation with both pH and volatile acidity. Note that the color is changing in both x and y axes:
  1. Color is transforming from blue and viloet to red and green from left to right, which means a downward change in citric acid level.
  2. Color is becoming blue and red from viloet and green from down to top, which also means a decreasing citric acid level as pH increases.
  1. Fixed acidity is in negative correlation with both pH and volatile acidity.
  1. Note that there are mostly square shapes in the bottom left of the plot. This is where the volatile acidity and pH are both in low levels.
  2. The square levels disappear as pH or volatile acidity increases in y or x axis. There are more triangles in bottom right and upper left corners.
  3. The fixed acidity is lowest in the upper right corner where the pH and volatile acidity are both highest.
  1. Fixed acidity is in positive correlation with citric acid.

Linear model depicting the relationship between pH, Volatile Acidity, Fixed Acidity and Citric Acid

A linear model is built to estimate the pH value with 3 other acidity variables given as inputs.

## 
## Calls:
## m1: lm(formula = I(pH) ~ I(log(volatile.acidity + 1)), data = RedWineQuality)
## m2: lm(formula = I(pH) ~ I(log(volatile.acidity + 1)) + fixed.acidity, 
##     data = RedWineQuality)
## m3: lm(formula = I(pH) ~ I(log(volatile.acidity + 1)) + fixed.acidity + 
##     citric.acid, data = RedWineQuality)
## 
## ==========================================================================
##                                      m1            m2            m3       
## --------------------------------------------------------------------------
##   (Intercept)                       3.180***      3.771***      3.776***  
##                                    (0.014)       (0.020)       (0.020)    
##   I(log(volatile.acidity + 1))      0.314***      0.078**      -0.010     
##                                    (0.033)       (0.025)       (0.030)    
##   fixed.acidity                                  -0.059***     -0.051***  
##                                                  (0.002)       (0.002)

## --------------------------------------------------------------------------

pH = 3.764 + -0.01xlog(volatile acidity+1) + -0051xfixed acidity + -0.124xcitric acid.

The r-squared value is 0.479 which is much less than 1 which means that the model is far from estimating the pH value with 3 acidity variables as input.

In the Quality vs Acidity vs Alcohol plot, I have sketched the change of alcohol value in the samples on the original Quality vs Volatile Acidity plot. It is displayed that alcohol value does not change with volatile acidity but the color only changes as the quality varies.

All of the findings are coinciding with the findings in bivariate analysis.

OPTIONAL: Did you create any models with your dataset? Discuss the
strengths and limitations of your model.

I created 2 linear models:

  1. A linear model with inputs log of volatile acidity, alcohol, total sulfur dioxide and chlorides, and quality as output.

My linear models has some drawbacks:

  • I only took some of the variables included in the dataset to construct the model. For example, I could add the density vaiable also.

  • Other factors which definitely affect the quality of a wine are not included in tha dataset. The wineyard, kind of grape, different flavors, bottling process may also be important.

  • If all other factors are included, the reliability of the model would increase.

  1. A linear model with fixed and volatile acidity and citric acid as inputs and pH as output.
  • The second model may also require extra variables to be reliable since the r-squared values seem low.

Description One

It is an interesting finding that total and free sulfur dioxide which are in negative correlation with the quality of the wine have right skewed histograms, in contrat with other variables such as acidity, chlorides and alcohol.

It means that most of the wine samples have low sulfur dioxide levels and this may not be used as a very strong differentiator for setting quality of wine.

This finding is interesting to see the effect of a variable with right or left skewed histogram on the resultant variable with a normal distribution.
